Throughout the landlocked Bolivia, there is still a vivid memory of the coastline lost to Chile as a result of the bloody conflict of the 19th century over resources; alive and eager to sail the Pacific again.
These hopes may have become the boldest in decades, as Bolivia awaits an international court decision that will take place on October 1 as a result of five years of debate.
“Bolivia has the energy, the spirit of unity and the mental balance and, of course, they are waiting for a positive result,” said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadilla.
Many Bolivians will be watching the International Court of Justice in large screens across the country, hoping that the tribunal in The Hague will be able to support Bolivia's statement that, after decades of intense negotiations, Chile is obliged to negotiate for Bolivia's sovereign access to the sea.
Evo Morales, the charismatic president of the indigenous peoples of Bolivia, who is waging a difficult battle for re-election next year, is also looking forward to a decision to be made on Monday.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific,” he said at the end of August.
