The Netherlands-based UN body does not have the authority to dispose of Chilean territory and has already stated that it will not affect the outcome of possible negotiations.
The fact that the International Court of Justice’s decision was made only six months after the last arguments were heard suggests that the case “wasn’t complicated,” says Pas Zarate, a Chilean expert on international law.
For the past four years, the Bolivian case has not progressed, but on the contrary, it has been postponed all the time.
“The current Bolivian administration has taken advantage of the problem of access to the sea for criminal purposes,” Zarate said.
According to her, Morales’ bellicose rhetoric destroyed Chile’s last benevolence.
Bolivia and Chile will continue negotiations at some point, but after that it will be extremely difficult to hold discussions.
The two countries have not had diplomatic relations since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodr<0xC3><0xAD>guez Velce, the representative of Bolivia in The Hague, disagrees that the court’s decision was made too quickly.
Monday will bring Bolivia “an exceptional opportunity to begin a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance “to put an end to 139 years of disagreement with mutual benefit,” he said.
Calzadilla also disagrees that Morales, still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents, is using the naval problem as a political trump card.
