John Edward: Knowledge of languages is of great importance to the citizens of the world
Scotland’s independent schools continue the tradition of brilliant education, which was once again confirmed in 2018: outstanding exam results have demonstrated individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other socially significant disciplines.
These schools are part of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), where more than 30,000 students are trained throughout Scotland, seeking to provide the highest level of services for students and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further higher education, their chosen career, as well as for the status of citizens of the world.
As part of the educational sector, which is responsible for the development and implementation of the individual school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, you call to his mind.
If you speak to him in his native language, you are turning to his heart.”
This is convincing evidence that we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships with and trust the citizens of other countries.
According to the results of this year’s latest exams, we see that languages occupy a leading position in league tables and have the highest score on the results of exams in independent schools.
A total of 68 per cent of students who studied foreign languages received the highest grade “A”.
Data from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students received an “A” in Mandarin, while 72 percent of students studying German, 69 percent of students studying French, and 63 percent of students studying Spanish also received an “A.”
This proves that in independent schools in Scotland, foreign languages are undoubtedly considered vital for children and young people in the future.
Currently, language subjects are in the same demand as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and other educational institutions.
A survey conducted by the UK’s Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that, among the reasons that made it difficult for employers to fill vacancies, 17 per cent had a lack of language skills.
Thus, language skills are increasingly becoming the key to a successful future career for young people.
Given that more promising jobs require language skills, these skills are needed in a globalized world.
Regardless of what profession the student chooses, if he learns a second language, in the future he will gain a real advantage by mastering another additional skill that will be useful to him throughout his further life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who knows several foreign languages a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak well enough in a foreign language to support the conversation, and French was the only language with a two-digit percentage — it is spoken by 15 percent of respondents.
That’s why investing in language education is so important right now.
Knowledge of several languages, especially the languages of countries with developing economies, will give children more chances to find a good job.
In schools in Scotland, there is a fairly large gap in terms of the languages that are taught – each school has its own set of languages.
A number of schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered most important to the UK in light of the country’s future development until 2020 – such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interests may be, independent schools will always have a choice of several languages with faculty members who are specialists in these languages.
Scotland’s independent schools aim to create a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds for them.
At the present time, it cannot be denied that in the global business environment, languages remain vital to the future development of the country, and this should be appropriately reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages really need to be seen as “the skills of international communication.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, providing diversity and benefits to young people in Scotland.
It has to be done.
John Edwards, Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
