North Korea Says It Won't "Categorically" Unilaterally Disarm Without Confidence
North Korea's foreign minister said at the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were fueling mistrust of the United States and that his country would under no circumstances unilaterally abandon its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “substantial measures of good will” last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site and committing not to build up nuclear weapons stockpiles and developing nuclear technologies.
“However, we do not observe a symmetrical reaction from the United States,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances, we will not be able to unilaterally take action on disarmament first.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s already-sounding complaints about Washington’s resistance to the “step-by-step” approach to denuclearization that North Korea would be rewarded for incremental steps, his statement seemed important in the sense that it did not reject a unilateral denuclearization-free approach.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between the current U.S. president and the North Korean leader held in Singapore on June 12; then Kim promised to start moving towards the “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula.”
North Korea is seeking to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington also resists calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The U.S. insists that ‘denuclearization must be done first,’ and raises the level of pressure through sanctions to enforce its goal and even objects to a ‘declaration of an end to the war,’” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can put us on our knees is a utopian dream of people who don’t know us.
But the real problem is that the ongoing sanctions increase our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention the plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding, “If South Korea, not the United States, were a party to this denuclearization issue, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not be like this.”
However, the tone of Ri’s speech differed sharply from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea’s missile targeting of the U.S. mainland was inevitable after “Mr. President of Evil” Trump called Kim “a suicide bomber.”
Trump, who threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea last year at the UN, praised Kim for his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said there was still much more to be done, and the sanctions should remain in place until North Korea disarms.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not set any deadlines for the process: “Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should encourage Pyongyang for the steps that have been taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The Security Council’s imposition of sanctions must continue actively and compulsorily until we see complete, definitive and confirmed denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously stepped up sanctions against North Korea since 2006, seeking to cut off funding for Pyongyang ' s nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly summit and said after the meeting that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his latest trip has failed.
In July, he left Pyongyang, saying progress had been made, but within hours of that visit, North Korea condemned him for “bandit demands.”
North Korea promised at a meeting with Moon this month to dismantle the missile complex, as well as the nuclear complex, if the United States, for its part, takes “appropriate measures.”
According to him, Kim told him that the “appropriate measures” he was talking about were security guarantees that Trump promised in Singapore, as well as actions aimed at normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students learn to rest on special courses.
The new course, introduced this year at Harvard University, helped all undergraduates learn to sleep more and fight the chauvinistic culture of continuous caffeine consumption with the goal of waking up “overnight.”
One of the academics found that the most successful students in the world often have no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chaser, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
After its opening, he got excited by the idea of introducing such a course, having made a preliminary report on the impact of lack of sleep on learning processes.
“At the end of my report, a girl came up to me and said, ‘I’m really sorry that I only learned about it now that I’m almost finished with my studies.’
She said no one ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, first offered to students this year, talks about how a healthy sleep habit contributes to academic and sports performance, as well as how it improves a person’s overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s Health Service, says the university decided to introduce this course after it was discovered that students were experiencing severe sleep deprivation during the study week.
The lesson lasts one hour, students perform a number of interactive tasks.
In one of the sections of the course, an image of the room in the dormitory is offered, where students, pressing on coffee cups, curtains, trainers and books, receive information on how each of these actions and substances - coffee, light, which cause lack of sleep - affect sports results, and how much is enough to get.
In another section, participants learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
