The inventor of the World Wide Web plans to launch a new Internet for Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup that claims to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company based on the open platform Berners-Lee Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and which people to give access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that Inrupt’s goal was to gain “world domination.”
“We have to do it now,” he says of his startup.
“This is a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid technology, which allows people to create their own “personal online data stores” or PODs.
It can contain lists of contacts, affairs, as well as a calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools to work with data.
The application works on the same principle as Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify – everything can be used in one browser and at the same time.
The uniqueness of a personal online data storage is that it is fully managed by the user, who can access any necessary information.
The company calls this principle “personal empowerment through data.”
According to CEO John Bruce, the idea of Inrupt is that the company has provided the resources, processes and relevant skills to make Solid accessible to everyone.
The company currently includes Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several full-time developers contracted to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to build their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not in talks with Facebook and Google about whether his company should make radical changes that will change all of their business models overnight.
“We don’t ask them for permission.”
In his Medium post published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that “Inrupt’s mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem to protect the integrity and quality of a new network built on Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet by creating a consortium of the World Wide Web at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee’s voice has sounded quite influential in debates about net neutrality.
Even launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Internet Foundation, and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic about this next era of the Internet,” says Berners-Lee.
Bernard Vann: a church servant awarded the Victoria Cross during the First World War
In the history of the Church of England, only one warrior priest was awarded the Victoria Cross during the First World War, and this event was celebrated in his hometown 100 years later.
Lt. Col. Bernard Vann was awarded this award on 29 September 1918 for his participation in the attack on Bellenglize and Loucourt.
Unfortunately, he was killed by a sniper four days later, never knowing that he had received the highest British military award.
The monument to this event was solemnly unveiled by his two grandchildren at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire, on Saturday.
One of his grandsons, Michael Vann, said it was “very symbolic” that the monument was opened exactly 100 years after his grandfather received the award.
According to the London Gazette of 29 September 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann conducted his battalion through the Canal Saint-Canten "in a very thick fog and under heavy fire of field guns and machine guns."
Later, he threw himself on the line of fire and, with "the greatest courage", led the group forward, and then with one hand threw a field gun, knocking down three soldiers of the unit.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just over a month before the end of the war.
The 72-year-old grandson of the hero Michael Vann said that “he could hardly have done the same heroic thing, but it humiliates.”
He and his brother Dr. James Vann also laid the wreath at the end of the parade, which was led by the Imperial Youth Orchestra Brentwood.
Michael Vann said that "it is a great honor for him to take part in the parade" and added that "the virtue of a true hero is confirmed by the support that will be given by many people."
