National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
A new study, conducted at one of the Scottish Highlands estates, aims to show how bats use the landscape in search of food.
It is to be hoped that the obtained data will allow a new look at the behavior of unique winged mammals and will help in further activities to preserve the species.
The study, organized by scientists from the National Fund of Scotland, will explore common netopyri, soprano netopyri, as well as brown long-haired bats and Dobanton night owls inhabiting Inverewe Gardens, Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be installed at some points around the site to monitor the actions of bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile site surveys using hand-held detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of screams, as well as the types of activities for which different groups of these animals are responsible.
A habitat map will then be drawn up and a report prepared to create a detailed picture of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, NTS Nature Conservation Advisor, hopes these results will show which habitats are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the main directions of work for habitat management, such as the formation of meadows, as well as ways of maintaining forest arrays in a state optimal for bats and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and across the UK has declined significantly over the past century.
They are at risk of extinction due to construction and development works that affect their habitat and loss of habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can pose a danger, as well as adhesive tape for flies, chemical treatment of building materials and hunting of domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, their nocturnal hunting habits are such that their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a complex echo-location technique to accurately identify obstacles on the flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes the issue of the bat population very seriously.
The organization employs ten trained experts who regularly conduct surveys, field inspections, and sometimes rescue work.
The organisation has even created Scotland’s first and only bat reserve at the Threeave estate in Damfries and Galloway, home to eight out of ten species of Scottish bats.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the perfect territory for them.
“Here at Threeave, it’s a great place for bats,” he says.
“There are old buildings, a lot of old trees and all the elements of a good habitat.
But much about bats remains unknown, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
He recalled the importance of verifying the presence of bats before carrying out maintenance within private ownership, since the unintentional destruction of one nest could result in the death of up to 400 females and young individuals, and possibly even the destruction of the entire local population.
Flying mice are protected by law, their destruction, grazing or destruction of their habitat is illegal.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish officer with the bat conservation fund, is calling on the public to help.
She says, “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we just don’t know how many separate species live.”
